  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Music on the Move,\" published by the University of Michigan Press in 2020, has established its relevance in academic discourse through measurable citations and indications of scholarly uptake. The work's influence is further suggested by its commercial presence on platforms like Amazon and Goodreads, indicating a broader engagement beyond traditional academic circles.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Since its publication in 2020, \"Music on the Move\" has demonstrated its impact primarily through citations, with a total of 16 academic references noted. This metric reflects a solid foundation of scholarly uptake, indicating that the book has provided valuable contributions to its field, despite an absence of mentions in public platforms such as Wikipedia or social media.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The inferred roles suggest a strong commercial linkage, evidenced by the book's availability on prominent online marketplaces like Amazon and Goodreads. Such commercial channels enhance the visibility of the publication, fostering engagement with a readership that may extend beyond academia into the general public, although direct public discourse metrics remain absent.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The presence of commercial visibility not only signifies a healthy market interest but also highlights the book's relevance in contemporary discussions around its subject matter. This indicates that \"Music on the Move\" is potentially appealing not just as an academic title, but also as a resource for those interested in the cultural and social implications of music.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In conclusion, while \"Music on the Move\" does not yet have strong evidence of community discourse or online engagement platforms, its academic citations and commercial presence signal a degree of recognition that underscores its thematic relevance. As the book continues to be utilized in both academic and non-academic contexts, further examination of its long-term impact will be critical to fully understanding its contributions to the field of music studies.</p>",
